hire, England":"Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, Anglie","Spencercombe, Devonshire, England":"Devon, Anglie","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, Anglie"},"da":{"1515–1 Aug 1617":"1515–1. august 1617","1479–1539":"1479–1539","1513–1617":"1513–1617","1510–1550":"1510–1550","1537–1617":"1537–1617","1515–1617":"1515–1617","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1513":"1513","1600":"1600","1479":"1479","1510":"1510","18 Aug 1539":"18. august 1539","1 Aug 1617":"1. august 1617","1617":"1617","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1537":"1537","Balderton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Balderton, Nottinghamshire, England","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, England","Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, England":"Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, England","Spencercombe, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"nl":{"1515–1 Aug 1617":"1515–1 augustus 1617","1479–1539":"1479–1539","1513–1617":"1513–1617","1510–1550":"1510–1550","1537–1617":"1537–1617","1515–1617":"1515–1617","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1513":"1513","1600":"1600","1479":"1479","1510":"1510","18 Aug 1539":"18 augustus 1539","1 Aug 1617":"1 augustus 1617","1617":"1617","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1537":"1537","Balderton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Balderton, Nottinghamshire, England","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, England","Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, England":"Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, England","Spencercombe, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"en":{"1515–1 Aug 1617":"1515–1 August 1617","1479–1539":"1479–1539","1513–1617":"1513–1617","1510–1550":"1510–1550","1537–1617":"1537–1617","1515–1617":"1515–1617","1550":"1550","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1513":"1513","1600":"1600","1479":"1479","1510":"1510","18 Aug 1539":"18 August 1539","1 Aug 1617":"1 August 1617","1617":"1617","1539":"1539","1549":"1549","1515":"1515","1537":"1537","Balderton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Balderton, Nottinghamshire, England","Sidmouth, Devon, England":"Sidmouth, Devon, England","Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, England":"Biggleswade, Bedfordshire, England","Spencercombe, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Taley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Staveley in Derbyshire, Stayley in Lancashire (now called Stalybridge in Greater Manchester), or perhaps Staveley (Westmorland), Staveley (Lancashire), or Staveley (Yorkshire). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>stæf</i> ‘staff, stave, rod’ (genitive plural <i>stafa</i>) + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. Compare   Staveley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stailey","meanings":["English: variant of   Staley  ."]},{"name":"Staveley","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the four places called Staveley (in Lancashire, Yorkshire, Derbyshire, and Westmorland), or from Stalybridge in Greater Manchester, which was formerly known as Stavelegh. Compare   Staley  ."]}]},{"name":"Saley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of <b>Sawley</b>, probably a habitational name from Sawley (Yorkshire) near Clitheroe in Lancashire, since it was in this area that the modern name chiefly ramified. However, Sawley near Ripon (Yorkshire) and Sawley (Derbyshire) also gave rise to surnames in the medieval period. The Yorkshire placenames derive from Old English <i>salh</i> ‘willow, sallow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’, while the Derbyshire placename comes from Old English <i>salh</i> + <i>hlāw</i> ‘mound, hill’. Compare   Sall  .","French (northern): variant of   Salley  .","Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Šalej</b>: from a pet form of the old personal name <i>Šalamon</i> (see   Salamon  ), or a nickname from <i>šaliti se</i> ‘to joke, to jest’. It is formed with the dialect diminutive suffix <i>-ej</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Sall","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  African/Muslim Cheikh, Amadou, Mamadou, Aliou, Babacar, Oumar, Serigne.","English: habitational name from Salle (Norfolk) or Saul (Gloucestershire), both originally named with Old English <i>salh</i> ‘willow, sallow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’, but at some point losing the final syllable. Compare   Saley  .","English: post-medieval variant of   Sale  ."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":34,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":43,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":54,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":56,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":85,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Rose Taley Saley was born in 1515, in Devon, England. She married John Ingersol in 1501, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died on 1 August 1617, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, at the age of 102."},"et":{"1515–1 Aug 1617":"1515–1. august 1617","1479–1539":"1479–1539","1513–1617":"1513–1617","1510–1550":"1510–1550","1537–1617":"1537–1617","1515–1617":"1515–1617","1550":"1550","